My last comment on homeless vets, is in no way negative to people who need our help.  My point is that I can believe that 40% of homeless are vets, but that number (percentage) is not exclusive to Nam vets.  I feel really sorry for any vet that had troubles and has fallen on their luck, but to say the bulk are Nam vet, demeans WWII vets, Korean War vets, Peacetime vets that need help too.  The Nam vet homeless thing has been played out by so many homeless, who feel that they can get more and/or better support if people think they are vets.  Instead of fighting over numbers, America should help ALL HOMELESS.  Vets of any time deserve all the helping hand this country and its people can give.  It makes me sick to live in a country where a vet has to be homeless (that didn't even happen in the Soviet Union), or someone has to claim they are a vet to get someone to show sympathy or give a damn enough to help.<br><br>
Nam vets have had the toughest adjustment and some are still on the road home.  All Nam vet deserve credit for just coming back to the USA.  Too bad there was not a Campaign Medal for the USA and readjustment or maybe a campaign star for the Vietnam Service medal called something like Operation Homecoming and America doesn't give a damn Campaign.  It would be probabely the hardest earned campaign star for most vets.<br>
In the days of the Revolutionary War, the new American Army would light barn fires, to act as signals for those who lost there way back to their units.  I guess all that those of us that give a damn can do is to keep the home fires burning for those who have not made it all the way home yet.<br><br>
In regards to the Statistics, if anyone wants I can put up different stats with their sources.  Take Statistics for what they are-the only measure available and what conclusions are drawn from.  For Vietnam they maybe tough to swallow, but they are what is available and what will be used by future generations to explore history, when the last eyewitnesses are gone.  So stats, studies and facts have a definite place.  If the source is credible and the study and facts drawn from credible sources, I think they are credible and can be accepted.  Anyone can say anything, but not everyone is entitled to their own facts, so the truth has a place, even if it is only researched numbers.  Most of these numbers are the numbers for Nam, until someone can prove them wrong etc.  <br><br>
  
